# Are Gun Owners More Likely to Be Shot? A Comprehensive Analysis

## Introduction

The question of whether gun owners are more likely to be shot is a complex and contentious issue in the United States, a country with a high prevalence of firearms and a significant rate of gun-related injuries and deaths. This report aims to provide a detailed, evidence-based analysis of this question by synthesizing data from multiple reputable sources, including peer-reviewed studies, national surveys, and expert analyses. The report will explore correlations between gun ownership and firearm-related injuries or deaths, the contexts in which gun owners may be at risk, and the broader societal implications.

## Gun Ownership and Perceptions of Safety

A 2020 survey by SafeHome.org found that gun owners are twice as likely as non-owners to feel "extremely safe" in their homes (43% vs. 18%), regardless of whether they also have home security systems ([SafeHome.org Research Team, 2020](https://www.safehome.org/home-safety/gun-owners-feel-safer/)). The primary reasons cited for gun ownership were personal protection (74%) and property protection (54%). Gun owners also tend to own other home security measures more frequently than non-owners.

However, feeling safe does not necessarily equate to being safe. The presence of firearms in the home introduces risks that may not be immediately apparent to owners.

## Statistical Evidence on Gun Owners and Risk of Being Shot

### Increased Risk of Firearm-Related Deaths in Gun-Owning Households

Research indicates a statistically significant association between gun ownership and increased firearm homicide rates. Siegel, Ross, and King (2013) conducted a state-level analysis from 1981 to 2010 and found that for each percentage point increase in gun ownership, the firearm homicide rate increased by 0.9% ([Siegel et al., 2013](https://ajph.aphapublications.org/doi/10.2105/AJPH.2013.301409)). This suggests that higher gun prevalence correlates with higher firearm homicide rates.

Similarly, Kivisto et al. (2019) found that for every 10% increase in home gun ownership, the risk of someone in the household being killed rose by 13%, with women being disproportionately at risk, especially in cases of intimate partner homicide ([Reinberg, 2019](https://www.webmd.com/mental-health/news/20190722/guns-in-home-greater-odds-of-family-homicide)).

### Suicide and Self-Inflicted Gunshot Risk

A significant proportion of gun-related deaths among owners are suicides. Studies show that gun owners who are suicidal are more likely to use firearms to end their lives, contributing to higher rates of firearm suicide among gun-owning populations ([Chris Everett, 2018](https://www.quora.com/Is-it-just-a-fact-that-owning-a-gun-is-a-good-way-to-get-yourself-shot)).

### Accidental Shootings and Unsafe Storage

Data from the Harvard Injury Control Research Center reveal that states with higher gun prevalence also have higher rates of unintentional firearm deaths, including accidents involving children and young adults ([Miller et al., 2001](https://injuryprevention.bmj.com/content/7/1/15)). Unsafe storage practices exacerbate these risks.

### Gun Use in Self-Defense: Frequency and Legality

While many gun owners cite self-defense as a primary reason for ownership, surveys indicate that actual defensive gun use is relatively rare. Harvard surveys in 1996 and 1999 found that hostile gun displays against individuals were over three times more common than self-defense gun uses by individuals ([Hemenway et al., 2000](https://injuryprevention.bmj.com/content/6/4/263)). Moreover, a majority of self-defense gun uses reported were deemed probably illegal by criminal court judges, suggesting that many such incidents may not be socially or legally justified.

## Demographic and Behavioral Factors

Gun ownership correlates with certain demographic factors such as income, political affiliation, and geography. For example, Republicans and conservatives are more likely to own guns, with ownership rates higher in rural areas and the South ([Gallup, 2021](https://news.gallup.com/poll/355511/gun-owners-increasingly-cite-crime-reason-ownership.aspx)).

Behavioral factors, such as alcohol use and lack of safety training, also influence the likelihood of accidental or intentional shootings among gun owners ([Hemenway & Richardson, 1997](https://ajph.aphapublications.org/doi/10.2105/AJPH.87.2.286)).

